Reyes Daniel Ruiz, 34, was mostly interested in sexual images and videos of the account holders, US Attorney David L. Anderson and Federal Bureau of Investigation Special Agent in Charge John F. Bennett said in the statement.
Ruiz, who worked as a software engineer for Yahoo, admitted using the access he had to hack into about 6,000 Yahoo accounts, targeting younger women --- including his personal friends -- and work colleagues, the statement said.
"Once he had access to the Yahoo accounts, Ruiz admitted to compromising the iCloud, Facebook, Gmail, DropBox and other online accounts of the Yahoo users in search of more private images and videos," the office said.
He made copies of images and videos that he found and stored them at home, the US Attorney's office said.
Ruiz was charged with one count of computer intrusion and one count of interception of a wire communication, but under the plea agreement pleaded guilty to just the computer intrusion charge, the statement says.
Ruiz's defense counsel did not immediately respond to a call and email for comment Monday evening.
Ruiz is currently released on a $200,000 bond and has a sentencing hearing scheduled for February 3, 2020, the US attorney's office said. He could face five years in prison for the computer intrusion charge and a fine of $250,000, plus restitution, the office said in its statement.

Thank God finally someone understands my situation.
At that time, everything was different.
When I went to work for that company, it was changing the system of punch cards with a system of 3 hard drives that was larger than a closet. I remember that there was an operator in the mainframe room and 3 young ladies recording data. The system had large magnetic tapes to make backup copies.
process thinking was totally different. Now, everything is at the moment. I remember that the systems that were there were chained processes that did chained things and were long processes, for example, the billing that the girls recorded passed them a series of chained programs (which lasted all afternoon and ended at night) in which all tasks were performed.
I remember that the operator went to work when we (the programmers) left and he stayed until the process (processes) ended. If the chained process failed (and failed many times), my boss had to go, and the next day he told us what had happened and how he could solve it urgently ...

Well, I'm rolling up, I'm sorry. What I mean by all this, is that the mentality that was at that time was not oriented at all to the thinking of today. That's why it's hard for me to think like now.
I was the one who started a little to do things that the user could do from the screens of the different departments of the company (modify things, etc ...)

and it still costs me, because all those languages are outdated because the processes are no longer done that way.

Thank you very much and forgive for all the roll that I have told you.
